					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/modernmajorgeneral" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(274283); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=274283&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610183585" alt="ModernMajorGeneral" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=274283)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/modernmajorgeneral" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(274283); return false;" >ModernMajorGeneral</a></span> <span class="odate time_1547796216 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">18 Jan 2019 07:23</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4122674">
									

<p>This is well done, and I normally like this sort of writing, but it was even a little too dry for my taste. Novote.</p>
<p>I don't think the III/IV qualifying parameters make a whole lot of sense - neither are mutually exclusive of one another on a scale which should be stepped gradients of risk. The fact that someone was originally non-anomalous and contacted the Foundation has no relevance to whether they should be allowed to wear plainclothes or own gifted items, if someone who is compliant and cooperative is forbidden from doing so (why?). Maybe this could be a privilege incentive structure to encourage people to turn themselves in, but not if the criteria are closed to the public.</p>
<p>There may be intentional inconsistencies to demonstrate how the Foundation is still an arbitrary and repressive organisation, but it's not clear, and I don't really like that sort of device.</p>

							</div>

								
					
