															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/modernmajorgeneral" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(274283); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=274283&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610183585" alt="ModernMajorGeneral" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=274283)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/modernmajorgeneral" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(274283); return false;" >ModernMajorGeneral</a></span> <span class="odate time_1547802230 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">18 Jan 2019 09:03</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4122732">
									

<p>This is neither how scientists or security officers operate in real life. Scientists regularly humanise the objects of their study (see: any biologist, ever) and there are reasons why both modern hospitals and prisons (combined, a reasonable approximation for what the Foundation is) advise staff to refer to their charges by their names instead of Prisoner #10485 or whatever; it improves their behaviour and cooperation for zero cost. If you object to this you are objecting based on ideology, not practicality.</p>
<p>(Security/prison guards do ignore people's pronouns and names and refer to them by dehumanising designations, but this is <em>not an efficient way to run a system</em> - it is purely done for various security theater political purposes)</p>

							</div>

								
